Overview


Globally, floods are a major hazard, with wide-ranging social, economic and environmental impacts. This threat is growing annually, especially in coastal areas due to accelerating mean sea-level rises, as well as increasing population growth coupled with new construction in flood-vulnerable areas. Today, over 600 million people live in critical coastal zones, and almost 2/3rdof the worlds cities with more than 5 million inhabitants fall within such zones. Accurately predicting local flooding in urban areas is highly complex, in part because of the multitude of underground spaces that are often not properly accounted for. Furthermore, underground spaces present a priority risk during flood events with respect to timely evacuation. Incomplete knowledge poses significant logistical challenges in generating highly accurate maps of these priority risk areas.





Intellectual Merit


TheUrbanARKproject explored the use of high-resolution airborne and mobile ground-based LiDAR scanning to identify and survey high-risk underground spaces, which can pose extra dangers to residents, shoppers, workers, and commuters in those space. The existence of those spaces may also significantly impact the accuracy of a flood model. However, such sinks are not regularly included. Additionally, the LiDAR data were then used to refine flood prediction models and to develop immersive Virtual Reality applications as a communication tool to support communities and emergency planners.


To address the related problems of improved flood prediction and enhanced risk communication,UrbanARKfocused on the social, scientific and technical challenges of coastal flood Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) with a particular focus on underground spaces. In this program, explored the following questions:

How best to identify and volumetrically estimate underground spaces not captured in existing documentation by efficiently using opportunistic spatial surveying and imagery data;
How to rapidly and cost-effectively acquire high-resolution spatial survey data of the internal geometries of identified underground spaces;
How to (1) store, curate, and query these various data efficiently, (2) make them unifiable with other data, and (3) enable their access by non-technical officials and public stakeholders;
How to integrate spatial data of street-scale underground spaces with available regional spatial data to refine regional flood models to better model flood rates and inundation levels;
How to employ the high-resolution spatial data and refined flood models to improve emergency planning and risk communication to improve DRR and resilience of urban occupants;
How best to deliver highly localized flooding risk warning information to local officials and residents so that the relevancy of the information is clear and that those receiving the information feel that they have sufficient agency to take action (e.g. evacuate).






Broader Impacts:


This tri-partite project involving academics at Queens University Belfast in Northern Ireland, University College Dublin in the Republic of Ireland, and New York University in the United States also joined emergency services and municipal flood planners from these communities in a series of in-person, hybrid, and virtual peer-to-peer learning exercises throughout the projects duration.





The project generated award-winning publications and presentations and deeply involved community residents and local teachers from an economically-disadvantaged neighborhood in Southwest Brooklyn, NY. On two separate trips, a cadre of local students, residents, teachers, and community social service providers had the opportunity to not only meet and interact with the overseas teams but to help with local data collection. These efforts have produced multiple publicly accessible data sets and models and accompanying curricular materials of significant relevance for any high school student living in a coastal community. Based on this work, two local high school mentees won an award at the highly prestigious NYC Terra STEM fair.


